 Dear All,

          This note is primarily for the theoreticians, but is
          relevant to anybody who uses the Unix machines in KLB
          for file storage (for example, with NFS access from
          Windows).

BACKGROUND
==========

  As you know, the network of workstations has grown in a rather
  uncontrolled manner over the years, and as a result maintaining
  the system and keeping backups has become a nightmare. For
  example, if one machine has a problem it can stall the backup
  script and the day's backup is lost for machines further down
  the list. Factor in the number of machines, and the chances of
  the most recent backup being up to a month old become quite
  high. This is clearly a risk we do not wish to continue to take.

  An ad-hoc group (mainly David Bowler, Louise Dash, Andrew Fisher
  and Andrew Gormanly) has looked into the possibility of installing
  a file server or servers, which would be the home of important files
  for all users, and which would be meticulously backed up.  (We ran
  a system where I used to work with two file servers and many
  diskless workstations, and that was very successful).

  If we go ahead with this scheme, we would phase out the backups
  of the other machines on the network: important files would be
  assumed to be on the file server system.

WHAT ARE WE SUGGESTING?
=======================

Possible options for the hardware are

a) Build our own.

This will cost maybe 6000 pounds for parts, and will take at least a day
to build, install and configure.  We'd have about 300GB of disk on each,
using the very fast EIDE UDMA100 IBM drives, with hardware RAID cards.

b) Buy from Dell

This will cost about 11,600 pounds for two machines - but they're very
different.  We'd get 300GB of 10,000 rpm Ultra3 SCSI drives and a very
nice motherboard  - so, expensive, but also good.  They supply RedHat
installed, and have drivers for their hardware RAID cards.

c) Look at other suppliers

there's a firm who offer 600GB of RAID5 storage (with a proper journaled
filing system) for about 5500 pounds - so the same as Dell, but with twice
the space!

 A particular advantage of Dell is that they offer good maintenance deals.

 Some modifications would also be necessary to the network infrastructure -
in particular to add a gigabit port to handle the traffic to the server.
We had in mind adding a 3com SuperStackII 1100 with 24 100MBit ports and
a Gigabit port for about 600 pounds.


WHY AM I BOTHERING YOU?
=======================

  Money, of course.  As you can see, what we are proposing is
  going to cost a good deal.  The question is, how much are you
  willing to pay for the security of your data?

 We do not have enough in the Group account to cover this
 development, and it is after all only a major benefit to the
 theoreticians.  I'm asking, then, whether you have funds in
 existing grants which you could put towards this upgrade, or
 whether you can make provision in new grant proposals. It would
 be a legitimate use of Group funds to underwrite the scheme,
 provided we were sure we could recover the money.

WHAT DO I WANT YOU TO DO?
=========================

  Please let me know how much you can put towards the scheme.  Let
  me have a response EVEN IF YOUR ANSWER IS ZERO.  Of course, if
  you have technical comments on what is proposed (including
  reasons why you don't think it's a good idea) let me have those
  too.

    Tony
