The dream of cheap energy from nuclear fusion has been around for so
long that few still believe it can come true. The technical problems of
creating and then containing a burning plasma as hot as the Sun have
proved so difficult - and so expensive - that even the richest countries
have given up on many of their fusion research projects. But at long
last there's some good news. Researchers at the US National Fusion
Facility in San Diego have achieved a massive boost in the rate of
fusion at their experimental tokamak. That's giving fresh hope to the
fusion community, with researchers from Europe, Japan, Russia and Canada
now lobbying their governments to fund a new prototype reactor. 
http://www.newscientist.com/news/news.jsp?id=ns9999999


TWO'S A CROWD
In London last week, scientists who study twins gathered for their 10th
International Congress and warned that the world is going to be overrun
by twins and triplets. Indeed, if present trends continue, within a
decade a third of all people born in some countries will be a triplet.
Why? One reason for the huge rise in multiple births is increased use of
IVF. Doctors often implant more than one embryo to make a successful
pregnancy more likely. And taking fertility drugs to induce ovulation
could lead to several eggs being released at once. The epidemic of
multiple pregnancies could overwhelm hospitals as the births are more
likely to be accompanied by complications. 
http://www.newscientist.com/news/news.jsp?id=ns99991001


DESTINED TO DIVORCE
There may soon be too many of them, but twins do come in very handy when
scientists are trying to tease apart the influence of genes and the
environment. One such study reported at the International Congress on
Twin Studies suggests that while your genes won't lead you to the altar,
they might summon you to the divorce courts. The research shows that
genetic make-up has a strong influence on whether or not your marriage
will last - though not whether you'll get married in the first place.
http://www.newscientist.com/news/news.jsp?id=ns99991002


TAMING THE MULTIVERSE
You download a newsletter from New Scientist, scroll through it and stop
at a story. You think, "that's interesting" as you read these words. But
another you thinks, "what nonsense" and moves right on. And yet another
you lets out a cry, keels over and dies. 

What's going on? Just life as usual if you believe David Deutsch of the
University of Oxford. Deutsch is convinced that our Universe is part of
the multiverse, "a domain of parallel universes that comprises ultimate
reality". To find out more, at least one of your multiple selves should
pick up the print version of New Scientist and read on...


IT'S A BLAST
Whatever next. The US military is demanding explosives that won't blow
up. The idea, of course, is to develop explosives that won't explode
accidentally, but will blow up when they are deployed on the
battlefield. The ability to simulate explosions inside computers is
turning this seemingly impossible demand into reality. 

Read the full feature in New Scientist magazine.


PREPARE FOR THE WORST
And from bangs to bugs. Has the US gone wobbly over biological weapons?
Ken Alibek thinks so. In 1992, he defected from the Soviet Union and
blew the whistle on its Biopreparat biowarfare machine. The programme
was one of the great deceptions of the cold war, because the Soviet
Union had signed a treaty banning such work. At its height, Biopreparat
employed 10,000 scientists at 40 sites and Alibek was the programme's
second in command. His defection was a fabulous prize for the US. Now
he's a key researcher at an American biodefence contractor - and full of
dire warnings about the threat of bioterrorism. 
http://www.newscientist.com/opinion/opinterview.jsp?id=ns22995


REINVENTING THE WHEEL
The earliest known representation of a wheel is found on a
5,500-year-old clay tablet unearthed at Ur in Mesopotamia. But that
hasn't stopped a lawyer in Australia patenting the wheel under the new
Australian Innovation Patent system. According to local sources, the
lawyer has no immediate plans to patent fire. 
http://www.newscientist.com/opinion/opfeedback.jsp?id=ns229999#15


AND FINALLY...
Next time you are visiting your friends check if they made the same
mistake as thousands of others and bought a copy of James Joyce's
Ulysses or Finnegans Wake during a deep literary phase - but
unfortunately failed to get beyond the first few pages. Now tell them
the good news: reading something this difficult could help them lose
weight. Not a lot of weight, it's true, but the brain definitely burns
up more fuel when tackling a tough cognitive task. You can find out how
much more in The Last Word.
