Title:
Electronic-Structure-based Thermodynamic Theory of
Ordering in Multicomponent Alloys

Abstract:
A linear-response-type theory for atomic short-range order
in alloys with arbitrary number of component is presented.
The method is based on the electronic structure of the
high-temperature random alloy through multiple-scattering
theory and the coherent potential approximation for
configurational averaging. The high-T alloy's instabilities
to all possible chemical ordering are identified in a single
calculation, like phonon modes of single elemental solids.
In addition, the electronic origin for the alloys' most
favored ordering (i.e. low-T phase transition) can be
identified on a system-dependent basis.
Example binary and ternary alloys will be discussed, along
with a unique method to characterize the ordering given by
diffuse scattering intensities from multicomponent alloys.


