How to enjoy London SILVER - http://www.HowToEnjoyLondon.co.uk

This week GOLD subscribers are getting 14 events (including one where=20
the editor is offering subscribers a free pint in a pub, with live=20
music, this weekend!) to the five that SILVER subscribers are being=20
sent. You can upgrade to GOLD by sending ONLY =A312.50 (for=20
subscription up to, and including, September 2001) by postal order=20
(available from all U.K. post offices), International Money Order or=20
cheque. Please make payable to HOW TO ENJOY PUBLICATIONS and write=20
the e-mail, that you want your subscription sent to, very clearly on=20
the back. Send payment to: 'How to enjoy' Publications, PO Box 3081,=20
LONDON SW10 0TW, England (United Kingdom).

Now, the use of international languages feature in this issue and=20
will do so a lot more in future issues (see our use of Spanish and=20
Irish below). Did you know that our website already has banner=20
advertising in other languages? And did you know that YOU choose the=20
language you would like to see future advertising in? Check out our=20
continually updated website today, and make your choice of language.

Please e-mail london@howtoenjoy.co.uk with any questions you may have.

Now, let us continue with our enjoyment of London...


July 13 2001, Friday, 6.45pm and 8.45pm, FILM DIRECTORS FROM DENMARK=20
COVER DISTINCT TOPICS OF CARE AND HORROR IN RIVERSIDE DOUBLE-BILL.=20
Did you know that today is Harrison Ford's birthday? Maybe you did,=20
but we doubt whether you knew that earlier this week the Chicago-born=20
actor flew his helicopter above an American forest and rescued a boy=20
scout who had been "lost" overnight - a true story of care and=20
horror! Now, let us turn our attention to other actors in other=20
films: one in English and another in Danish! 'How to enjoy London'=20
subscribers have shown that they like films (more so in English, than=20
in other languages) and prefer to go to events after 6pm, so this=20
evening we are inviting you to the Riverside Studios. The first film=20
is entitled "Mifune" (1998, 98 mins) and is in Danish with English=20
sub-titles. It is followed by "The King is Alive" (2000, 110 mins).=20
The directors are Soren Krogh-Jacobson and Kristian Lerring=20
respectively. Only =A35.50 (=A34.50 for students) to see both
films. Reservations can be made by ringing the box office on 020 8237=20
1111. Location: Riverside Studios, Crisp Road, W6. Nearest tube=20
station: Hammersmith (Piccadilly, District and Hammersmith & City=20
lines).

July 14 2001, Saturday, 11am - 4pm, "MAEDA GAKUEN" - JAPANESE=20
FESTIVAL OF KARAOKE, DANCING, DRUMMING... AND EVEN SCOTTISH BAGPIPES!=20
A venue located very close to the tube station is promising you an=20
afternoon of Japanese tastes, culture and education. You might even=20
learn some of the language - that is if you can follow what the=20
karaoke singers will be singing about in the singing competition that=20
has been organised. Entry to the competition is open to all, so=20
people with good voices should get along early to get their name down=20
on the list. We are looking forward to hearing the drums - and we are=20
sure that the other 4,000 people expected will also want to hear the=20
drummers play! It promises to be a bit special this year as it is a=20
part of the Japanese Festival 2001. And why not end the day by=20
heading off to a French restaurant, after all it is Bastille Day!=20
Admission: =A31.50 Location: Playing Fields (not the Sports Ground),=20
off Queen's Drive, W3. Nearest tube station: North Ealing (Piccadilly=20
line).

July 15 2001, Sunday, from 9am for 11am, HELP CHILDREN IN OVER 70=20
COUNTRIES - JOIN WALKERS ON REGENT'S PARK STROLLERTHON. The Save the=20
Children website is calling their tenth 10-mile stroll through=20
London, 'that fabulous family fiesta of fun, fresh air and=20
fundraising'. And with six thousand people expected it promises to be=20
just that. The route followed will start at Regent's Park, going on=20
to the centre of London, then back again to finish in the same park.=20
Their website puts it another way by stating that it will, 'take in=20
many of the capital's favourite sights - as well as some little-known=20
treasures'. Participants get a goody bag with handbook, chocolate and=20
t-shirt (for that sunny weather, we are crossing our fingers for).=20
Starting times are staggered, so the earlier you come the sooner you=20
will be able to get away for other events listed below. Prices: =A35=20
for individuals and =A310 for families. Location: south side of=20
Regent's Park, NW1. Nearest tube station: Regent's Park (Bakerloo=20
line). To register telephone 020 7252 4141, or you can register in=20
person on the day (between 9am and 11am).=20

July 17 2001, Tuesday, 7.30pm, POESIA MEJICANA EN BIBLIOTECA DE=20
KENSINGTON, which means 'Mexican poetry in Kensington library'. We=20
hope to use more foreign languages within 'How to enjoy London' -=20
that way, most of you will learn something new... hopefully! Mario=20
Martinez will be your host for an evening of poetical writings from a=20
Latin country, on the other side of the world. Admission: =A35,
=A33 for students. Location: Kensington Library, Hornton Street, W8.=20
Nearest tube station: High Street Kensington (Circle and District=20
lines).

July 18 2001, Wednesday, 7.30pm, HAMMERSMITH VENUE HOSTS IRISH=20
DOCUMENTARIES ABOUT ISLE OF ARAN, B=C0TAICHEAN-IASGAICH, ETC. Any
ideas what a b=E1taichean-iasgaich is? Well, it means fishing boat,
and there are sure to be several of these in the films you will see=20
this evening. Yes, you will have a great opportunity to see a=20
documentary double-bill with Robert Flaherty's "Man of Aran" (75=20
mins) and George Storey's "The making of 'The Man of Aran'" (45=20
mins). They are documentaries with, 'Breathtaking scenery of Ireland'=20
according to the brochure we picked up from Hammersmith's Irish=20
Centre. You can see them both for only =A35. Location: Irish Centre,=20
Blacks Road, W6. Nearest tube station: Hammersmith (Piccadilly,=20
District, Hammersmith & City lines).


